(lp4
VMy travels to Afghanistan
p5
aVbegan many, many years ago
p6
aVon the eastern border of my country,
p7
aVmy homeland, Poland.
p8
aVI was walking through the forests
p9
aVof my grandmother's tales.
p10
aVA land where every field hides a grave,
p11
aVwhere millions of people
p12
aVhave been deported or killed
p13
aVin the 20th century.
p14
aa(lp15
VBehind the destruction,
p16
aVI found a soul of places.
p17
aVI met humble people.
p18
aVI heard their prayer
p19
aVand ate their bread.
p20
aVThen I have been walking East for 20 years \u2014
p21
aVfrom Eastern Europe to Central Asia \u2014
p22
aVthrough the Caucasus Mountains,
p23
aVMiddle East,
p24
aVNorth Africa,
p25
aVRussia.
p26
aVAnd I ever met more humble people.
p27
aVAnd I shared their bread and their prayer.
p28
aVThis is why I went to Afghanistan.
p29
aa(lp30
VOne day, I crossed the bridge
p31
aVover the Oxus River.
p32
aVI was alone on foot.
p33
aVAnd the Afghan soldier was so surprised to see me
p34
aVthat he forgot to stamp my passport.
p35
aVBut he gave me a cup of tea.
p36
aVAnd I understood
p37
aVthat his surprise was my protection.
p38
aa(lp39
VSo I have been walking and traveling,
p40
aVby horses, by yak, by truck, by hitchhiking,
p41
aVfrom Iran's border
p42
aVto the bottom, to the edge of the Wakhan Corridor.
p43
aVAnd in this way
p44
aVI could find noor, the hidden light of Afghanistan.
p45
aVMy only weapon
p46
aVwas my notebook and my Leica.
p47
aVI heard prayers of the Sufi \u2014
p48
aVhumble Muslims,
p49
aVhated by the Taliban.
p50
aVHidden river,
p51
aVinterconnected with the mysticism
p52
aVfrom Gibraltar to India.
p53
aVThe mosque where the respectful foreigner
p54
aVis showered with blessings
p55
aVand with tears,
p56
aVand welcomed as a gift.
p57
aa(lp58
VWhat do we know
p59
aVabout the country and the people
p60
aVthat we pretend to protect,
p61
aVabout the villages
p62
aVwhere the only one medicine
p63
aVto kill the pain and to stop the hunger
p64
aVis opium?
p65
aVThese are opium-addicted people
p66
aVon the roofs of Kabul
p67
aV10 years after the beginning of our war.
p68
aVThese are the nomad girls
p69
aVwho became prostitutes for Afghan businessmen.
p70
aa(lp71
VWhat do we know about the women
p72
aV10 years after the war?
p73
aVClothed in this nylon bag,
p74
aVmade in China,
p75
aVwith the name of burqa.
p76
aVI saw one day,
p77
aVthe largest school in Afghanistan,
p78
aVa girls' school.
p79
aV13,000 girls
p80
aVstudying here
p81
aVin the rooms underground,
p82
aVfull of scorpions.
p83
aVAnd their love [for studying]
p84
aVwas so big that I cried.
p85
aa(lp86
VWhat do we know
p87
aVabout the death threats by the Taliban
p88
aVnailed on the doors
p89
aVof the people who dare to send their daughters to school as in Balkh?
p90
aVThe region is not secure, but full of the Taliban,
p91
aVand they did it.
p92
aa(lp93
VMy aim is to give a voice
p94
aVto the silent people,
p95
aVto show the hidden lights
p96
aVbehind the curtain of the great game,
p97
aVthe small worlds ignored by the media
p98
aVand the prophets of a global conflict.
p99
aa(lp100
VThanks.
p101
aa(lp102
V(Applause)
